# HyperFetch Branding

## Core Identity

HyperFetch IS the SDK — the type-safe API layer for TypeScript apps.

- **Not** just a fetcher
- **Not** just a generator
- **The** API layer for TypeScript apps

## Positioning Statement

> One SDK. Any API. Fully typed.

Use this exact tagline in hero sections, READMEs, and social. Do not paraphrase.

## Supporting Line

> The type-safe API layer for TypeScript apps. Connect to REST, GraphQL, Firebase, WebSockets, SSE — all with one consistent interface and the best type safety in the ecosystem.

## Three Pillars (always in this order)

1. **Universal** — One interface for REST, GraphQL, Firebase, WebSockets, SSE
2. **Best type safety** — End-to-end TypeScript types from schema to response, zero `any`
3. **CLI generation** — Generate fully typed SDKs from OpenAPI/Swagger schemas (this is the accelerator, not the identity)

## Messaging Hierarchy

### What to say first
- Works with ANY API through one interface
- Best type safety in the ecosystem
- Works in every framework and environment

### What to say second
- Generate SDKs from OpenAPI schemas
- Built-in caching, retries, offline support
- React hooks with optimistic updates

### What to say last
- Devtools (HyperFlow)
- Advanced features (serialization, replay, queuing internals)
- Platform roadmap

## Progressive Reveal

Show complexity in layers. Never dump everything at once.

| Level | What to show | Where |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | `createClient` → `createRequest` → `.send()` | Landing hero, Getting Started |
| 2 | React hooks (`useFetch`, `useSubmit`) | React docs, README examples |
| 3 | Caching, retries, offline, optimistic updates | Core concepts, guides |
| 4 | Adapters, sockets, devtools, CLI | Integration docs, advanced |

## Tone

- Confident, not arrogant
- Technical, not academic
- Benefit-first, not feature-first
- Show, don't tell — always include code

## Words to use
- "type-safe", "typed", "autocompletion"
- "one interface", "universal", "any API"
- "zero guesswork", "no `any`"
- "works everywhere"

## Words to avoid
- "simple" (everyone says this)
- "easy" (subjective and unhelpful)
- "flexible" (too vague)
- "powerful" (overused)
- "supports everything" (sounds like marketing)
- "best in class" without specifics
